0.body: In this book, we explore the fundamentals of the Feo language, namely its syntax, core data structures, and flow control features. If you have some prior programming experience, this will hopefully be enough to get you started with Feo.
0.title: Language Tour

1.body: In Feo, everything is an expression. That means everything evaluates to some value, like 2 * 3, which is 6.
1.title: Overly Simplifed Overview

10.body:
In Feo, strings can be written as text surrounded by double quotes. "This is a string" Also, they can span multiple lines. "Multi-line
string!" Under the hood, strings are just Rust Strings, which are encoded with UTF-8 , and are able to contain any valid unicode. "🖕🏻こんにちはFeo 👺"
10.title: Strings

11.title: Concatenation

12.body:
Feo supports common string escape sequences. Here's all of them: Sequences Result \n Newline \r Carriage Return \t Tab \" Double Quote \\ Backslash \0 Null Terminator For example, to include double quote (") character in a string literal, it must be escaped by placing a backslash (\) character before it. "Here's a double quote: \"" Another example: // A Windows filepath C:\Users\Nobu
"C:\\Users\\Nobu"
12.title: Escape Sequences

14.body:
A Boolean can be either true or false. Atom values :true and :false are also evaluated as Booleans. Feo defines a handful of operators that work with Booleans. && evaluates the right hand side if the left hand side is true. || evaluates the right hand side if the left hand side is false. You can also use and and or keywords instead of && and || respectively. false && false // => false
false && true // => false
true && false // => false
true && true // => true
false and true // => false false || false // => false
false || true // => true
true || false // => true
true || true // => true
true or false // => true Feo supports negation of Booleans using either the ! or not unary operators. !true // => false
not false // => true
14.title: Booleans

15.body: Feo's main number types are Integers and Floats.
15.title: Integers And Floats

16.body:
Integers are "whole" numbers. Hexadecimal integers start with 0x. 15
-83
0xBADC0FFEE // 50159747054 Feo has several operators that work with Integers. 1 + 1 // => 2
4 - 2 // => 2
6 / 3 // => 2
1 * 2 // => 2
5 % 3 // => 2 2 > 1 // => true
2 < 1 // => false
2 >= 1 // => true
2 <= 1 // => false
16.title: Integers

17.body:
Floats are numbers that have a decimal point. 1.0
2.2
-0.44 The same operators work for Floats as well. 1.0 + 1.4 // => 2.4
5.0 - 1.5 // => 3.5
5.0 / 2.0 // => 2.5
3.0 * 3.1 // => 9.3 2.0 > 1.0 // => true
2.0 < 1.0 // => false
2.0 >= 1.0 // => true
2.0 <= 1.0 // => false
17.title: Floats

19.body:
null is just a value that shows that the object is referring to nothing. null == null // => true
null <= 7.3 // => false
19.title: Null

2.body:
Feo has 7 primitive types and 3 complex ones: null // Null
_ // "Empty" value, equal to everything
1, 2, 4 // Integers
3.45 // Floats
true, false // Booleans
"Hello!" // Strings
:ok // Atoms [:error, 1, "blah", false] // Lists
{age: 16, name: "Nobu"} // Objects
func (x, y) x + y // Functions
2.title: Types

20.body:
_ is an "empty" value, which is equal to anything. _ >= 123 // => true
_ == "hello" // => true
20.title: Empty

21.body:
Lists are ordered collections of values. They're one of the most common data structures in Feo. Lists are heterogeneous , meaning the elements of a list can be of different types. [:err, "something wrong happened"]
[["abc", "hello"], 23, 3.14] Under the hood, lists are just Rust Vectors. A built-in function append is provided to append a value to a list. names := ["Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas"]
names |> append("Sol") names // ["Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas", "Sol"] You can index an element in a list by using []. ages := [16, 15, 15, 14]
ages[0] // 16
21.title: Lists

22.body:
An object is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities. nobu := { name: "Nobu", cool?: true, email: "nobu.bichanna@gmail.com",
} Once you have an object, the properties contained can be accessed using the .something accessor syntax. nobu.cool? // true
22.title: Objects

23.body:
The assignment operator := binds values on the right side to names on the left, potentially by destructuring an object or list. For example: a : = 1 // a is 1 [b, c] := [4, "string"] // b is 4, and c is "string" {first_name: name} := {first_name: "Nobuharu", last_name: "Shimazu"} // name is "Nobuharu" The reassignment operator = binds values on the right side to names on the left, but only when those variables already exist. If the variable doesn't exist in the current scope, the operator ascends up parent scopes until it reaches the global scope to find the last scope where that name was bound. n := 1
m := 2
{ n = 3 m := 4
}
n // 3
m // 2
23.title: Assignment

25.title: Named Functions

26.body:
Feo provides syntax for passing the result of one function to the arguments of another function, the pipe operator (|>). This is similar in functionality to the same operator in Elixir or F#. The pipe operator allows you to chain function calls without using a plethora of parenthesis. names := []
append(append(append(append(names, "Nobu"), "Sol"), "Damian"), "Thomas")
names // ["Nobu", "Sol", "Damian", "Thomas"] This can be expressed more naturally using the pipe operator, eliminating the need to track parenthesis closure. names
|> append("Nobu")
|> append("Sol")
|> append("Damian")
|> append("Thomas") Each line of this expression applies the function to the result of the previous line.
26.title: Pipe Operator

27.body:
Anonymous functions can be defined with a similar syntax: func run() { add := func(x, y) x + y add(1, 2) // 3
}
27.title: Anonymous Functions

28.title: Match Expression

29.body:
A match expression can be used to destructure values that contain other values, such as lists and objects. match [number % 3, number % 5] { [0, 0] -> "FizzBuzz", [0, _] -> "Fizz", [_, 0] -> "Buzz", [a, b] -> a + b,
}
29.title: Destructuring

3.title: Assignment

30.body:
There is also a short-hand match, which is known as the ternary operator. damian_stinks := false
command := damian_stinks ? "go take a shower" : "go take a nap" // de-sugars to this:
command := match damian_stinks { true -> "go take a shower", _ -> "go take a nap",
}
30.title: Ternary Operator

31.title: Modules

32.body: Until now errors have never been mentioned, but if you have tried out the examples you have probably seen some. There are two distinguishable kinds of errors: syntax errors and exceptions .
32.title: Exceptions

33.body:
Syntax errors, also known as parsing errors, are perhaps the most common kind of complaint you get while you are still learning Feo. some_file:1:14 error: expected ']'
names["hello"
33.title: Syntax Errors

34.body:
Even if an expression is syntactically correct, it may cause an error when an attempt is made to execute it: some_file:1:11 zero division error: division by zero
n := 10 / 0
34.title: Runtime Exceptions

35.title: Handling Runtime Exceptions

36.body: Programs may name their own exceptions by creating a new exception: error(:user_defined, "user-defined error!")
36.title: User-defined Runtime Errors

37.title: Testing

38.body: Feo’s standard library is quite extensive, offering a wide range of facilities as indicated by the long table of contents listed below. The library contains built-in modules (written in Rust) that provide access to system functionality such as file I/O that would otherwise be inaccessible to Feo programmers, as well as modules written in Feo that provide standardized solutions for many problems that occur in everyday programming.
38.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » The Feo Standard Library
38.title: The Feo Standard Library

39.body: The Feo interpreter has a number of functions and types built into it that are always available. All of them are listed here. abs import int float string atom type len append pop keys values args env get print println eprint eprintln error
39.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » Built-in Functions » Built-in Functions
39.title: Built-in Functions

4.title: Control Flows

40.body: abs returns the absolute value of a number.
40.title: abs(x)

42.body: int converts x to an integer.
42.title: int(x)

43.body: float converts x to a float.
43.title: float(x)

44.body: string converts x to a string.
44.title: string(x)

45.body:
type returns the type of x as an atom: :int, :float, :string, :atom, :list, or :object. pi := 3.1415
type(pi) // :float
45.title: type(x)

46.body:
lenreturns the length of a string, a list, or an object. list := ["Hello", "World"]
len(list) // 2
46.title: len(xs)

47.body:
append creates a new list or string, x appended to xs. list := [1, 2]
list = append(list, 3)
list // [1, 2, 3]
47.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » Built-in Functions » append(xs, x)
47.title: append(xs, x)

48.body:
pop creates a new list or string, the item at index i popped from xs, and returns a list of the new value and the popped value. i is optional and defaults to len(xs) - 1. list := [1, 2, 3]
[list, popped] := pop(list) // list is [1, 2], and popped is 3
48.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » Built-in Functions » pop(xs, i)
48.title: pop(xs, i)

49.body:
keys returns a list of the keys of the object obj. obj := {name: "Nobu", email: "nobu.bichanna@gmail.com"}
keys(obj) // [:name, :email]
49.title: keys(obj)

5.title: Functions

50.body:
values returns a list of the values of the object obj. obj := {name: "Nobu", email: "nobu.bichanna@gmail.com"}
values(obj) // ["Nobu", "nobu.bichanna@gmail.com"]
50.title: values(obj)

51.body: args returns a list of command line arguments.
51.title: args()

52.body: env returns all environment variables as an object.
52.title: env()

53.body:
get returns the value of the item with the key key, which could be an atom or a string. It is unsafe (might throw an error). obj := {name: "Nobu"}
get(obj, :name) // "Nobu"
53.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » Built-in Functions » get(obj, key)
53.title: get(obj, key)

54.body: print prints x to the standard output stream. print("Hello, world\n")
54.title: print(x)

55.body: println prints x to the standard output stream with a new line at the end. println("Hello, world")
55.title: println(x)

56.body: eprint prints x to the standard error stream. eprint("something wrong happened!\n")
56.title: eprint(x)

57.body: eprintln prints x to the standard error stream with a new line at the end.` eprintln("something wrong happened!")
57.title: eprintln(x)

58.body:
error creates a new error with type t and msg. err := unsafe error(:some_error, "some error!")
err.error_type // :some_error
err.error_message // "some error!"
58.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » Built-in Functions » error(t, msg)
58.title: error(t, msg)

59.body: std library defines basic functions for working with Oak values and functions, iterators, and control flow. identity is default to_hex from_hex clamp slice clone range reverse map each filter reduce flatten append join zip partition unique first last take take_last find rfind index_of rindex_of contains? loop aloop
59.title: std

6.body:
It takes a value on the left and makes it the first argument to a function call on the right: func add(x, y) x + y
10 |> add(15) |> add(12) // 37
6.title: Pipe Operator

60.body: identity returns its first argument. "Hello" == identity("Hello") // true
60.title: identity(x)

61.body:
is returns a predicate that reports whether its argument is equal to x. f := is(2)
f(2) // true
f("a") // false
61.title: is(x)

62.body:
default returns x if x is not null, or base otherwise. It is useful when taking optional arguments in functions with default values. func some_func(n, times) { // times = 1 by default times := default(times, 2) // do something
}
62.title: default(x, base)

63.body: to_hex takes a number and returns its hexadecimal representation in a string. It fails for negative values. to_hex(50159747054) // "BADC0FFEE"
63.title: to_hex(n)

64.body: from_hex takes a hexadecimal representation of a number and parses it to an integer. It returns null if the input is not a valid hexadecimal number. from_hex("BADC0FFEE") // 50159747054
64.title: from_hex(s)

65.body: clamp takes values n, m and "clamps" or constrains it to the range [min, max], inclusive. If n > m, n takes priority and clams m down to the lower value. In the returned value, the following are guaranteed: min <= n <= max min <= m <= max n <= m
65.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » std » clamp(min, max, n, m)
65.title: clamp(min, max, n, m)

66.body:
slice takes an iterable xs (string or list) and returns a "slice" of the original from the range [min, max). The slice is a copy, and mutating it will not mutate the original. Both min and max are optional and will default to 0 and len(xs) respectively. name := "Sol David"
slice(name, 0, 3) // "Sol"
66.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » std » slice(xs, min, max)
66.title: slice(xs, min, max)

67.body:
clone takes any Feo value and produces a shallow copy of it that will not mutate if the original mutates. list := [1, 2, 3]
new_list := clone(list) [list, _] = pop(list) // list is [1, 2]
new_list // still [1, 2, 3]
67.title: clone(x)

68.body: range returns a list of numbers in range [start, end), incrementing by step. It is analogous to Python's range builtin, and will default to step = 0 and start = 0 when those optional values are missing. range(0, 11, 2) // [0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10]
68.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » std » range(start, end, step)
68.title: range(start, end, step)

69.body: reverse reverses the order of all elements in a given iterable, producing a copy. reverse([1, 2, 3]) // [3, 2, 1]
69.title: reverse(xs)

7.title: Comments

70.body: map produces a copy of the given iterable where each element has been put through some mapper predicate f. If f is a function, it receives arguments (element, index). [1, 2, 3] |> map(func(element, index) element * 5) // [5, 10, 15]
70.title: map(xs, f)

71.body:
each calls the given iterator function f for each element of the given iterable xs. The iterator function receives arguments (element, index). [1, 2, 3] |> each(func(element, index) print(element))
// prints "123" to the console
71.title: each(xs, f)

72.body:
filter produces an iterable containing only the elements of xs that return true when passed to the filter predicate f. If f is a function, it receives arguments (element, index). list := [10, 4, 23, 13, 45] |> filter(func(element, index) element >= 15)
list // [23, 45]
72.title: filter(xs, f)

73.body:
reduce accumulates elements of the iterable xs on a value, starting with seed and passing it to the reducer function f. The reducer receives arguments (accumulator, element, index). // an example "sum" function implemented with reduce
numbers |> reduce(0) <| func(accumulator, elem) accumulator + elem
73.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » std » reduce(xs, seed, f)
73.title: reduce(xs, seed, f)

74.body:
flatten takes a list of lists and flattens it to a list of elements. The flattening is only one level deep. list := [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5], [6, 7]]
flatten(list) // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
74.title: flatten(xs)

75.body:
append joins two iterable values (strings or lists) together, mutating the first argument xs. If mutation is not desired, use std.join. names := ["Nobu", "Damian"]
append(names, ["Sol", "Thomas"])
names // ["Nobu", "Damian", "Sol", "Thomas"]
75.title: append(xs, ys)

76.body:
join joins two iterable values (strings or lists) together, while mutating neither values. If efficiency is desired, used std.append. names := ["Nobu", "Damian"]
join(names, ["Sol", "Thomas"]) // ["Nobu", "Damian", "Sol", "Thomas"]
names // ["Nobu", "Damian"], not mutated
76.title: join(xs, ys)

77.body: zip "zips" together each pair of items from two iterables. If the zipper function is not given, each pair of items are put into a 2-element list. Otherwise, zipper is called on each pair of items and the result is placed into the resulting list. zip([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]) // => [[1, 2], [3, 4], [5, 6]] zip([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6], fn(a, b) a * b) // => [4, 10, 18]
77.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » std » zip(xs, ys, zipper)
77.title: zip(xs, ys, zipper)

78.body:
partition divides the sequence of items in the iterable xs into a list of lists (partitions). If by is an integer, each partition will contain that number of items. If by is a function, the partition will be cut anywhere the result of the function changes from one item to the next. For any other values of by, partition returns null. list := [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
partition(list, 3) // [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]
78.title: partition(xs, by)

79.body:
unique takes a list xs, and returns a similar list where no element of xs occurs twice in a row. Elements may occur twice in the list if they are separated by other elements. unique takes an optional pred predicate, by which elements' equality may be compared. unique runs in O(n) time. list := [1, 1, 2, 2, 3]
unique(list) // [1, 2, 3]
79.title: unique(xs, pred)

8.body:
For comments that extend beyond a single line, you might want to use multi-line comments that start with /* and end with */: /* Hello, world! This is a very very very very very very very long comment. I have a lot to say, so much that it will take multiple lines of comments.
*/
8.title: Multi-line Comment

80.body:
first returns the first item in an iterable. It's trivial, but useful to have in the stdlib for use in pipelines or iterators. name := "Nobu"
first(name) // "N"
80.title: first(xs)

81.body:
last returns the last item in an iterable. It's trivial, but useful to have in the stdlib for use in pipelines or iterators. name := "Nobu"
first(name) // "u"
81.title: last(xs)

82.body:
take accepts an iterable and returns a version of it containing the first N elements. email := "nobu.bichanna@gmail.com"
take(email, 4) // "nobu"
82.title: take(xs, n)

83.body:
take_last accepts an iterable and returns a version of it containing the last N elements. email := "nobu.bichanna@gmail.com"
take_last(email, 9) // "gmail.com"
83.title: take_last(xs, n)

84.body:
find returns the index of the first item in the iterable xs for which the predicate returns true. If no match is found, find returns -1. nobu? := is("Nobu")
names := ["Sol", "Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas", "Maks", "Nobu"]
find(names, nobu?) // 1
84.title: find(xs, pred)

85.body:
rfind returns the index of the last item in the iterable xs for which the predicate returns true, searching backwards from the end. If no match is found, rfind returns -1. nobu? := is("Nobu")
names := ["Sol", "Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas", "Maks", "Nobu"]
rfind(names, nobu?) // 5
85.title: rfind(xs, pred)

86.body:
index_of returns the index of the first item equal to x in the iterable xs. If no match is found, index_of returns -1. names := ["Sol", "Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas", "Maks", "Nobu"]
index_of(names, "Nobu") // 1
86.title: index_of(xs, x)

87.body:
// rindex_of returns the index of the last item equal to x in the iterable xs, searching backwards from the end. If no match is found, rindex_of returns -1. names := ["Sol", "Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas", "Maks", "Nobu"]
index_of(names, "Nobu") // 5
87.title: rindex_of(xs, x)

88.body:
contains? reports whether an iterable contains an item equal to x. names := ["Sol", "Nobu", "Damian", "Thomas", "Maks", "Nobu"]
contains?(names, "Nobu") // true
88.title: contains?(xs, x)

89.body:
loop takes a loop count max and a callback, and invokes the callback max times. It can be used to infinitely loop if max < 0. Callback is called with two arguments: count: the current loop count starting from 0 breaker: a function to be called to exit early from the loop, which takes an optional return value to be returned by the loop() call loop(100) <| func(count, breaker) { // prints "Hello, world!" to the console 100 times println("Hello, world!")
}
89.title: loop(max, f)

90.body:
aloop takes a loop count max and a callback, and invokes the callback max times asynchronously . It can be used to infinitely loop if max < 0. Callback is called with three arguments: count: the current loop count starting from 0 next: a function to be called when the current iteration is done done: a function to be called to exit early from the loop aloop(100) <| func(count, next, done) { // do something... next()
}
90.breadcrumbs: Standard Library » std » aloop(max, f, done)
90.title: aloop(max, f, done)
